[2] Bud rot - Colombia
Date: 7 Apr 2010
Source: Los Angeles Times [edited]
<http://www.latimes.com/features/health/la-fg-colombia-palms8-2010apr08,0,2512357.story>


In Puerto Wilches, Colombia, Edgar Barrera, superintendent of the
Bucarelia company's 12 000 acre oil palm grove, speaks of the palms'
death sentence. "What we have is a technological, economic and social
disaster."

He is referring to a mysterious, fast-spreading and deadly disease
called "PC" [bud rot] that has devastated oil palm plantations in
Colombia. More than 60 percent of Bucarelia's palms are dead or dying
because of it, and PC has destroyed more than half a million of his
company's trees, he said.

It's not just huge plantations that are suffering. A farmer who
plowed his life's savings into a 35 acre grove that was once highly
profitable is still coming to grips with the disaster. Since he first
noted signs of PC in 2007, the plague has killed 1200 of his 2000
trees. The surviving palms' days are numbered, he said.

The ravages of PC go beyond agriculture; the damage extends to
Colombia's drug fighting and energy policies. By decimating palm
groves, the disease is eliminating an alternative crop to coca,
cocaine's raw material, which is illegally grown in abundance
hereabout. It could also impede the government's mandate that by 2015
20 percent of all fuel burned by trucks and buses be made with
biofuels.

Fedepalma, the association of Colombian palm farmers, has mounted a
disease management program centering on hybrids.

[Byline: Chris Kraul]

